    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Arabs, Israelis and Fateful Choices</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jerry Rapp letter, commenting on Amira Hass's September 2 Op-Ed article on Israeli-Palestinian violence, disputes assertion that Palestinian misery arises from existence of Israeli settlements</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>When Amira Hass asserts that Palestinian misery arises from the existence of Israeli settlements, she displays a selective memory (Op-Ed, Sept. 2). Before there was a single Israeli settlement and the West Bank was under Arab control, Palestinians lived there under more miserable conditions than today.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>When Amira Hass asserts that Palestinian misery arises from the existence of Israeli settlements, she displays a selective memory (Op-Ed, Sept. 2). Before there was a single Israeli settlement and the West Bank was under Arab control, Palestinians lived there under more miserable conditions than today.</p>
        <p>At Taba, an Israeli proposal would have given the Palestinians some 97 percent of the West Bank. I don't recall any Arab government anywhere offering the Palestinians any land at any time in history.</p>
        <p>JERRY RAPP  Kew Gardens Hills, Queens  Sept. 2, 2001</p>
      </block>
